  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "At the rising of the sun.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when the sun had risen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " There seems at first a slight discrepancy between this and St. Matthew’s “while it was yet dark.” A morning haze, however, or the partial continuance of the gloom which had shrouded the city on the previous day, may well be thought of as harmonizing the two accounts.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
